<section id="fs-idm320811776" class="section-summary">
<title>Summary of Learning Outcomes</title>
<list id="fs-idm318687552" list-type="enumerated" start-value="8">
<item>What are the stages of the product life cycle?</item>
</list>
<para id="fs-idm351130912">After a product reaches the marketplace, it enters the product life cycle. This cycle typically has four stages: introduction, growth, maturity, and decline (and possibly death). Profit margins are usually small in the introductory phase, reach a peak at the end of the growth phase, and then decline.</para>
<para id="fs-idm342850704">Price indicates value, helps position a product in the marketplace, and is the means for earning a fair return on investment. If a price is too high, the product wonâ€™t sell well and the firm will lose money. If the price is too low, the firm may lose money even if the product sells well. Prices are set according to pricing objectives.</para>
</section>
